@NODE Option_HELP "HELP, H"

@{U}CLI options                   @{UU}  @{U}Workbench tooltypes           @{UU}

HELP | H			not supported


@{U}Explanation@{UU}:

Display  a short summary of valid options in the current CLI window.  If the
window  is  too  small to completely hold this information, you may redirect
the  output to a file (@{B}RunLame HELP >T:RunLame.olh@{UB}), which can be read using
a text editor.

@ENDNODE
##_____________________________________________________________________________

@NODE Option_GUIDE "GUIDE, G"

@{U}CLI options                   @{UU}  @{U}Workbench tooltypes           @{UU}

GUIDE | G			GUIDE | G		= USE


@{U}Explanation@{UU}:

Open an @{"AmigaGuide" LINK AmigaGuide_Explanation} help documentation for RunLame.  This happens directly at
startup  of RunLame and the form of the guide help depends on the setting of
RunLame.   If you use the @{"GUI" LINK Option_GFXUSERINTERFACE} and/or @{"API" LINK Option_APPICON} of RunLame, the guide help will be
asynchroneous, allowing manipulation of the @{"GUI" LINK Option_GFXUSERINTERFACE}/@{"API" LINK Option_APPICON} while reading the guide.
Otherwise the guide is synchroneous.

@ENDNODE
##_____________________________________________________________________________

@NODE Option_GFXUSERINTERFACE "GFXUSERINTERFACE, GUI"
@NEXT Option_APPICON

@{U}CLI options                   @{UU}  @{U}Workbench tooltypes           @{UU}

GFXUSERINTERFACE | GUI		GFXUSERINTERFACE | GUI	= USE


@{U}Explanation@{UU}:

The  @{"GUI" LINK GUI_Explanation}  is always invoked when the @{"COMMANDLINE" LINK Option_COMMANDLINE} parameter is omissed. Use
the  GUI  option  to force RunLame to open the GUI, even if @{"COMMANDLINE" LINK Option_COMMANDLINE} has
been  specified, whose argument in this case will appear in the command line
string  gadget.  The GUI is going to appear centered to the mouse pointer on
the  default  public  screen,  I  just  liked the behaviour of the ReqChange
redirected  requesters.   The GUI is mainly divided in two parts:  the menu,
and  the  window.  Both, menu and window gadgets correspond directly to each
other.   Both,  menu  items and gadgets support shortcuts.  The shortcuts of
the  menu  are  the  same as the shortcuts of the gadgets, but they need the
left  Amiga  key  qualifier  pressed  additionally.  So both, `I'(or i') and
LAMIGA+`I'(or  `i')  result  in  the same action as if the Instruction Cache
gadget or menu item would have been clicked/selected.  The shortcuts are not
listed  in  this documentation for the user can directly determine them from
the GUI.  The menu shortcuts are shown right to the appropriate menu item if
it  supports shortcuts.  The gadget shortcuts are case insensitive (like the
menu shortcuts).  The underlined character of the gadget description text is
the  corresponing shortcut key, not to be pressed with additional qualifiers
except for optionally SHIFT.  If the launched command line would produce any
outputs  to the CLI window, this  output is redirected to a automatically on
the  default  public  screen  opening  CON:   window,  which  can  be closed
asynchroneously  (meaning  that  RunLame  is  not  running any more, but the
window  remains  on  the  default  public  screen and can be closed when not
needed  any  more).   In addition to be able to input the command line using
the   string   gadget   or   the  filerequester,  it  is  possible  to  drop
(multiselected)  icons  from the Workbench into the GUI window.  The name(s)
of  the  corresponding object(s) appear(s) in the command line string gadget
added  to the  end of the previous contents (assuming @{"NOAPPEND" LINK Option_APPEND} has not been
supplied).  Using  the  @{"PATH" LINK Option_PATH}  parameter makes it possible to set an initial
drawer for the file requester (normally the file requester uses the current
directory as initial drawer)

One  special shortcut is the `HELP' key.  If pressed, the online @{"AmigaGuide" LINK AmigaGuide_Explanation}
documentation  is  shown  asynchroneously.  This means you need not to close
the guide before using the GUI again.  If no guide appears, you should check
if the documentation (@{B}RunLame.guide@{UB}) resides in the AmigaGuide path (defined
in @{B}ENV:AmigaGuide/Path@{UB}).  If you want to place the documentation outside the
AmigaGuide path, you have to specify the location using @{"GUIDENAME" LINK Option_GUIDENAME}.

The pull down menu (shortcuts not documented):

  @{U}main menu strip@{UU}:         @{U}sub menu strips@{UU}:

 +======================+ +=============+ +=============+ +=============+
 |RunLame		| |VBR location | |Caches	| |Burst modes	|
 +======================+ +=============+ +=============+ +=============+
 |@{"About" LINK GUI_About}			| | @{"$0" LINK Option_VBR}		| | @{"Instruction" LINK Option_INSTCACHE}	| | @{"Instruction" LINK Option_INSTBURST}	|
 |~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~| | @{"FAST memory" LINK Option_VBR}	| | @{"Data" LINK Option_DATACACHE}	| | @{"Data" LINK Option_DATABURST}	|
 |VBR location		| +-------------+ | @{"External" LINK Option_EXTERNALCACHE}	| +-------------+
 |Caches		|		  +-------------+		
 |Burst modes		|
 |  @{"Copyback mode" LINK Option_COPYBACK}	|
 |~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~|
 |  @{"Screen" LINK Option_SCREEN}		|
 |  @{"Visible screen" LINK Option_VISIBLE}	|
 |~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~|
 |@{"Enter commandline" LINK GUI_EnterCommandline}	|
 |@{"Open file requester" LINK GUI_OpenFReq}	|
 |@{"Launch commandline" LINK GUI_Launch}	|
 |~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~|
 |@{"Quit" LINK GUI_Quit}			|
 +----------------------+


  @{U}application window@{UU}: 

			 +-----------------------+
 			 |@{"·" LINK GUI_Quit} RunLame	    @{" " SYSTEM}@{" " SYSTEM}	 |
			 +-----------------------+
			 |+---------------------+|
			 ||@{" $0  " LINK Option_VBR} VBR location	||
			 |+---------------------+|
			 ||@{"  " LINK Option_INSTCACHE} Instruction Cache	||
			 ||@{"  " LINK Option_DATACACHE} Data Cache	||
			 ||@{"  " LINK Option_EXTERNALCACHE} External Caches	||
			 |+---------------------+|
			 ||@{"  " LINK Option_INSTBURST} Instruction Burst	||
			 ||@{"  " LINK Option_DATABURST} Data Burst	||
			 |+---------------------+|
			 ||@{"  " LINK Option_COPYBACK} Copyback		||
			 |+---------------------+|
			 ||@{"  " LINK Option_SCREEN} Screen @{"  " LINK Option_VISIBLE} Visible||
			 |+---------------------+|
			 | @{"  " LINK GUI_OpenFReq}@{"                 " LINK Option_COMMANDLINE}	 |
			 | @{" Launch commandline " LINK GUI_Launch}	 |
			 +-----------------------+

@ENDNODE
##_____________________________________________________________________________

@NODE GUI_About "About menu item"
@PREV Option_GFXUSERINTERFACE
@NEXT Option_GFXUSERINTERFACE

@{U}Explanation@{UU}:

A  short copyright notice is shown in a requester.  Same effect if you press
`?'.

@ENDNODE
##_____________________________________________________________________________

@NODE GUI_EnterCommandline "Enter commandline menu item"
@PREV Option_GFXUSERINTERFACE
@NEXT Option_GFXUSERINTERFACE

@{U}Explanation@{UU}:

Activate  the  commandline  string  gadget  which  enables  you to specify a
@{"COMMANDLINE" LINK Option_COMMANDLINE}.

You  may  also  press  `ENTER',`RETURN' or `TAB' to activate the commandline
string gadget.

@ENDNODE
##_____________________________________________________________________________

@NODE GUI_OpenFReq "Open file requester"
@PREV Option_GFXUSERINTERFACE
@NEXT Option_GFXUSERINTERFACE

@{U}Explanation@{UU}:

Open an ASL file requester.  You then may select a file whose path/name will
be appended to the commandline, depending on the @{"APPEND" LINK Option_APPEND} switch.

@ENDNODE
##_____________________________________________________________________________

@NODE GUI_Launch "Launch commandline"
@PREV Option_GFXUSERINTERFACE
@NEXT Option_GFXUSERINTERFACE

@{U}Explanation@{UU}:

This  action  ignites  the  execution  of  the  command  line.   The current
configuration  of RunLame is active during the execution of the command line
defined  in  the  command  line  string gadget.  After execution the changed
settings  of  your  system  are reset to the state active before.  So if you
know  that for example the demo called @{B}ObsoleteFX@{UB} will not run with active
data  cache,  but an active instruction cache would speed it up, forthermore
it won't run in burst mode and with VBR in another location than $0.l, use:

 @{B}RunLame GUI INSTCACHE NODATACACHE NOBURST INVISIBLE ObsoleteFX@{UB}

You  will  see  the  correct  setting  reflected in the gadgets and the menu
items.  If you now launch the command line, the following will happen:

 assumed system settings before launching:
  data cache active        | instruction cache active
  data burst mode active   | instruction burst mode inactive
  VBR in Fast RAM at position p

 system settings during execution of ObsoleteFX (launched):
  data cache inactive      | instruction cache active
  data burst mode inactive | instruction burst mode inactive
  VBR at $0.l

 system settings after execution of ObsoleteFX:
  data cache active        | instruction cache active
  data burst mode active   | instruction burst mode inactive
  VBR in Fast RAM at position p

@ENDNODE
##_____________________________________________________________________________

@NODE GUI_Quit "Quit RunLame"
@PREV Option_GFXUSERINTERFACE
@NEXT Option_GFXUSERINTERFACE

@{U}Explanation@{UU}:

The  RunLame  task/process  will stop existing, all held resources are given
back to the system.  The looping mode (activated by @{"LOOP" LINK Option_LOOP}) is stopped, too.

You may quickly exit RunLame by pressing the `ESC' key.

@ENDNODE
##_____________________________________________________________________________

@NODE Option_APPICON "APPICON, API"
@PREV Option_GFXUSERINTERFACE

@{U}CLI options                   @{UU}  @{U}Workbench tooltypes           @{UU}

APPICON | API			APPICON | API		= USE


@{U}Explanation@{UU}:

The  @{"API" LINK API_Explanation}  supplies a comfortable method of immediate starting objects whose
icons  are  dropped  into  it.   It is possible to multiselect icons, so the
command  line  consists of all objects in the order they have been selected.
To  quit  RunLame,  double  click  the  API.   When  a command line has been
supplied  at  the startup of RunLame, all icons/objects dropped into the API
are  appended  to  this  command  line,  then  the  command line is executed
(assuming  @{"NOAPPEND" LINK Option_APPEND} has not been supplied). When too many icons are dropped
into  the  API  ,  the Workbench screen beeps before command line execution.
Output produced by the command line goes to the CLI when RunLame was started
not  from  the Workbench.  The icon representing the API is the same as used
for RunLame (if this is missing, the system default icon is used) , the name
is the same as RunLame has on your disk.

@ENDNODE
##_____________________________________________________________________________

@NODE Option_LOOP "LOOP, L"

@{U}CLI options                   @{UU}  @{U}Workbench tooltypes           @{UU}

LOOP | L			LOOP | L		= YES


@{U}Explanation@{UU}:

The  LOOP  option  can  only be used together with @{"API" LINK Option_APPICON} and/or @{"GUI" LINK Option_GFXUSERINTERFACE}. When you
want to start several command lines in a sequence, it is quite unconfortable
to  always start RunLame for each command line execution.  LOOP works around
this  problem  by forcing  RunLame to pop up the @{"API" LINK API_Explanation} and/or @{"GUI" LINK GUI_Explanation} again after
each  command line execution, until it is quitted by double clicking the API
or  quitting  the  GUI.  When the appropriate input object (API/GUI) pops up
again, the initial command line  given at startup  of RunLame (@{"COMMANDLINE" LINK Option_COMMANDLINE})
is  always  inserted at  front of the command line  created using the  input
object.  Furthermore all settings  of the former command line execution  are
preserved.

Example:

 @{B}RunLame APPICON LOOP dir@{UB}

 You  can  now  drop  icons of Workbech drawers into the application icon to
 list  their  contents.  The @{B}dir@{UB} command is always assumed to be the first
 part  in  the  command  line.   Same  applies to startup from Workbench via
 (multi-)selected icons.

@ENDNODE
##_____________________________________________________________________________

@NODE Option_DEFAULTS "DEFAULTS, NODEFAULTS, D, ND"

@{U}CLI options                   @{UU}  @{U}Workbench tooltypes           @{UU}

DEFAULTS | D			DEFAULTS | D		= USE
NODEFAULTS | ND			DEFAULTS | D		= NO


@{U}Explanation@{UU}:

If  you  specify  DEFAULTS  at startup of RunLame, the following options are
assumed:

@{"SCREEN" LINK Option_SCREEN}, @{"VISIBLE" LINK Option_VISIBLE}, @{"NOCACHE" LINK Option_CACHE}, @{"NOINSTCACHE" LINK Option_INSTCACHE}, @{"NODATACACHE" LINK Option_DATACACHE}, @{"NOBURST" LINK Option_BURST},
@{"NOINSTBURST" LINK Option_INSTBURST}, @{"NODATABURST" LINK Option_DATABURST}, @{"NOCOPYBACK" LINK Option_COPYBACK}, @{"NOEXTERNALCACHE" LINK Option_EXTERNALCACHE}, @{"VBRTO0" LINK Option_VBR}, @{"APPEND" LINK Option_APPEND}

The  DEFAULTS option is always assumed to be set.  So if you want to disable
all  caches, the copyback mode and want to degrade the display, you need not
to  specify  one  of  these options.  Those options are really obsolete, but
were  implemented  for completeness.  Furthermore the specification of those
options in script files (though leaving them out would have the same effect)
increases  the readability of the script file because every user not knowing
which  defaults  are  set by RunLame can see what really is going to happen.
So the following usages of RunLame affect in the same:
@{B}
 RunLame foobar

 RunLame D S NC NB NCB NEC NVBR CL foobar

 RunLame BURST NIC NOEXTERNALCACHE CL=foobar

 RunLame SCREEN NOINSTCACHE NODATACACHE NOINSTBURST NODATABURST NOCOPYBACK
         NOEXTERNALCACHE VBRTO0 DEFAULTS COMMANDLINE=foobar
@{UB}
The  NODEFAULTS  switch  forces  RunLame to configure itself to fit best the
current  system  settings.   So if you specify NODEFAULTS and don't override
any  of  the  settings,  RunLame  will  change  nothing  in the system while
executing the commandline.

Furthermore  specification  of  options  overrides  the  DEFAULTS/NODEFAULTS
settings  of  RunLame.   So  it's  possible to start programs in your normal
environment,  with  some  parameters  just  changed,  not all possible.  The
parameters changed are set to the same value each time you use this feature,
but  the  rest  of the settings are the built in defaults/the current system
setting.

Example:

 @{B}RunLame NODEFAULTS VBRTO0 SCREEN INVISIBLE ObsoleteFX@{UB}

 assumed system settings before RunLame usage:
  data cache active        | instruction cache active
  data burst mode active   | instruction burst mode inactive
  external caches inactive | copyback mode active
  VBR in Fast RAM at position p

 system settings during execution of ObsoleteFX:
  data cache active        | instruction cache active
  data burst mode active   | instruction burst mode inactive
  external caches inactive | copyback mode inactive
  VBR at $0.l
  screenmode changed to PAL, screen blanked,
  sprite resolution changed to lores and sprites turned off

 system settings after execution of ObsoleteFX:
  data cache active        | instruction cache active
  data burst mode active   | instruction burst mode inactive
  external caches inactive | copyback mode active
  VBR in Fast RAM at position p

@ENDNODE
##_____________________________________________________________________________

@NODE Option_SCREEN "SCREEN, NOSCREEN, S, NS"

@{U}CLI options                   @{UU}  @{U}Workbench tooltypes           @{UU}

SCREEN | S			SCREEN | S		= ON
NOSCREEN | NS			SCREEN | S		= OFF


@{U}Explanation@{UU}:

Non  system  conform  programmed  software might cause problems when started
from  within  another  screen  mode  than  PAL.   This might effect in weird
running  bitplanes  or  anything  else, but when it happens, you will become
aware  of  it,  believe  me.   To avoid these annoying problems, the default
option  called  SCREEN  opens  a  2x2  pixels wide screen with depth 1 (this
should  eat  up  not  very  much  memory :-) before starting the problematic
program.  Due to the existance of several screen mode promotion tools I have
to  point  out  that  it is not very clever to allow promotion of the screen
opened  by  RunLame.   Furthermore  some programs use an incorrect method to
turn  off  sprites  which  results in running pixel patterns (similar to the
above  decribed  bitplane effect).  RunLame tries to avoid this problem when
the SCREEN option is active.  In favour to RunLame's multitasking abilities,
the  sprite  DMA is not shut down, but redirected to a NULL sprite (which is
the  most  effective method to turn off sprites).  This method cannot avoid,
that  the  pointer  is reactived by any window becoming active after turning
off the sprites (refer to @{"Problems - solutions - corner" LINK ProblemsSolutions}).

@ENDNODE
##_____________________________________________________________________________

@NODE Option_VISIBLE "VISIBLE, INVISIBLE, V, NV"

@{U}CLI options                   @{UU}  @{U}Workbench tooltypes           @{UU}

VISIBLE | V			VISIBLE | V		= YES
INVISIBLE | NV			VISIBLE | V		= NO


@{U}Explanation@{UU}:

The  VISIBLE  option  keeps  the  previous  frontmost  screen  visible,  but
displayed  in  PAL.   This  is handy when the program you start with RunLame
outputs  to any window opened/opening on the previous frontmost screen.  For
programs  that  don't  output anything to the previous frontmost screen, use
the  INVISIBLE  option,  so  the  current display contents are hidden.  This
option only makes sense together with the @{"SCREEN" LINK Option_SCREEN} option.

@ENDNODE
##_____________________________________________________________________________

@NODE Option_CACHE "CACHE, NOCACHE, C, NC"

@{U}CLI options                   @{UU}  @{U}Workbench tooltypes           @{UU}

CACHE | C			CACHE | C		= ON
NOCACHE | NC			CACHE | C		= OFF


@{U}Explanation@{UU}:

This option controls all processor caches installed in the system.  Refer to
@{"INSTCACHE" LINK Option_INSTCACHE} and @{"DATACACHE" LINK Option_DATACACHE} for more detailed description.

@ENDNODE
##_____________________________________________________________________________

@NODE Option_INSTCACHE "INSTCACHE, NOINSTCACHE, IC, NIC"

@{U}CLI options                   @{UU}  @{U}Workbench tooltypes           @{UU}

INSTCACHE | IC			INSTCACHE | IC		= ON
NOINSTCACHE | NIC		INSTCACHE | IC		= OFF


@{U}Explanation@{UU}:

This  option  allows  you to control the instruction cache of the @{"CPU" LINK CPU_Explanation}.  Some
lame  programs  use  self  modifying  code  which  can lead to inconsistency
between  cache  contents and memory contents.  The result in most cases is a
system crash.  In this case turn off the instruction cache.

@ENDNODE
##_____________________________________________________________________________

@NODE Option_DATACACHE "DATACACHE, NODATACACHE, DC, NDC"

@{U}CLI options                   @{UU}  @{U}Workbench tooltypes           @{UU}

DATACACHE | DC			DATACACHE | DC		= ON
NODATACACHE | NDC		DATACACHE | DC		= OFF


@{U}Explanation@{UU}:

This  option  allows  you  to  control the data cache of the @{"CPU" LINK CPU_Explanation}.  Some @{"lame" LINK Lame_Explanation}
programs  modify  memory  data whilst it is read by a DMA channel, which can
lead  to  inconsistency  between  cache  contents  and memory contents.  The
result  in  most  cases  is a weird display, a crash or other anomalies.  In
this case turn off the data cache.

@ENDNODE
##_____________________________________________________________________________

@NODE Option_BURST "BURST, NOBURST, B, NB"

@{U}CLI options                   @{UU}  @{U}Workbench tooltypes           @{UU}

BURST | B			BURST | B		= ON
NOBURST | NB			BURST | B		= OFF


@{U}Explanation@{UU}:

This option lets you control the burst modes of the @{"CPU" LINK CPU_Explanation} caches all together.
Refer to @{"INSTBURST" LINK Option_INSTBURST} and @{"DATABURST" LINK Option_DATABURST} for more detailed description.

@ENDNODE
##_____________________________________________________________________________

@NODE Option_INSTBURST "INSTBURST, NOINSTBURST, IB, NIB"

@{U}CLI options                   @{UU}  @{U}Workbench tooltypes           @{UU}

INSTBURST | IB			INSTBURST | IB		= ON
NOINSTBURST | NIB		INSTBURST | IB		= OFF


@{U}Explanation@{UU}:

This option allows you to control the burst mode of the instruction cache of
the @{"CPU" LINK CPU_Explanation}. Disabling might fix strange behaviour of programs.

@ENDNODE
##_____________________________________________________________________________

@NODE Option_DATABURST "DATABURST, NODATABURST, DB, NDB"

@{U}CLI options                   @{UU}  @{U}Workbench tooltypes           @{UU}

DATABURST | DB			DATABURST | DB		= ON
NODATABURST | NDB		DATABURST | DB		= OFF


@{U}Explanation@{UU}:

This  option  allows  you to control the burst mode of the data cache of the
@{"CPU" LINK CPU_Explanation}.  Disabling might fix strange behaviour of programs.

@ENDNODE
##_____________________________________________________________________________

@NODE Option_COPYBACK "COPYBACK, NOCOPYBACK, CB, NCB"

@{U}CLI options                   @{UU}  @{U}Workbench tooltypes           @{UU}

COPYBACK | CB			COPYBACK | CB		= YES
NOCOPYBACK | NCB		COPYBACK | CB		= NO


@{U}Explanation@{UU}:

If none of the other option helps improving the behaviour of a @{"lame" LINK Lame_Explanation} program,
try changing the state of the copyback mode of the @{"CPU" LINK CPU_Explanation}.

@ENDNODE
##_____________________________________________________________________________

@NODE Option_EXTERNALCACHE "EXTERNALCACHE, NOEXTERNALCACHE, EC, NEC"

@{U}CLI options                   @{UU}  @{U}Workbench tooltypes           @{UU}

EXTERNALCACHE | EC		EXTERNALCACHE | EC	= ON
NOEXTERNALCACHE | NEC		EXTERNALCACHE | EC	= OFF


@{U}Explanation@{UU}:

This  option  should give you control over externally installed caches.  Due
to  lack  of  such hardware, this could not be tested.  Furthermore it seems
not  possible  to  check  for  existence of such caches in a system friendly
manner.  Therefore this option is not accessible.

@ENDNODE
##_____________________________________________________________________________

@NODE Option_VBR "VBRTOFAST, VBRTO0, VBRTO, VBR, NVBR"

@{U}CLI options                   @{UU}  @{U}Workbench tooltypes           @{UU}

VBRTOFAST | VBR			VBRTO | VBR		= FAST
VBRTO0 | NVBR			VBRTO | VBR		= 0


@{U}Explanation@{UU}:

This option gives you control over the @{"VBR" LINK VBR_Explanation} of the @{"CPU" LINK CPU_Explanation}. Most of old programs
using  interrupts  don't  consider  the  fact,  that 68010+ CPUs have a VBR.
Since  Kickstart V36 the VBR is not granted to point to address $0 (which is
located  in CHIP memory).  If such a @{"lame" LINK Lame_Explanation} program accesses CPU vectors which
are offsets to the VBR, and the VBR doesn't point to $0, the CPU jumps to an
undefined  memory  location.  Most of the crashes can be fixed by moving the
VBR to location $0.

@ENDNODE
##_____________________________________________________________________________

@NODE Option_APPEND "APPEND, NOAPPEND, APN, NAPN"

@{U}CLI options                   @{UU}  @{U}Workbench tooltypes           @{UU}

APPEND | APN			APPEND | APN		= YES
NOAPPEND | NAPN			APPEND | APN		= NO


@{U}Explanation@{UU}:

The  APPEND  option  is  set  by  default, but can be overriden by NOAPPEND.
APPEND  is responsible for the appending behaviour of the file requester (or
the  application  window feature  and the @{"APPICON" LINK Option_APPICON} feature).  If you specify
NOAPPEND,  the  command  line  will  always  be overwritten by any new given
filenames.   This  works  for  the  application icon, the application window
feature and the file requester.  You see, when you use @{"APPICON" LINK Option_APPICON} and NOAPPEND
together,  it's  senseless  to  supply  a startup command line, because it's
going to be overwritten by the objects you drop into the application icon.

@ENDNODE
##_____________________________________________________________________________

@NODE Option_PATH "PATH, P"

@{U}CLI options                   @{UU}  @{U}Workbench tooltypes           @{UU}

PATH | P		= path	PATH | P		= path


@{U}Explanation@{UU}:

Using  this  option  you  may  specify  a  default startup path for the file
requester of the @{"GUI" LINK Option_GFXUSERINTERFACE}.  This is useful if the program you want to execute is
not located in the current directory.

@ENDNODE
##_____________________________________________________________________________

@NODE Option_GUIDENAME "GUIDENAME, GN"

@{U}CLI options                   @{UU}  @{U}Workbench tooltypes           @{UU}

GUIDENAME | GN		= name	GUIDENAME | GN		= name


@{U}Explanation@{UU}:

Using  this  option  you may specify a default path/name for the @{"guide" LINK Option_GUIDE} help
document. This is useful, if you press the HELP key in the @{"GUI" LINK Option_GFXUSERINTERFACE} and no @{"guide" LINK Option_GUIDE}
help appears.

@ENDNODE
##_____________________________________________________________________________

@NODE Option_COMMANDLINE "COMMANDLINE, CL"

@{U}CLI options                   @{UU}  @{U}Workbench tooltypes           @{UU}

COMMANDLINE | CL	= cmd	COMMANDLINE | CL	= cmd


@{U}Explanation@{UU}:

The  command line may consist of same complex format as could be used in the
AmigaDOS  shell.   The  only  thing  you  must  pay attention to is that the
COMMANDLINE  option  is  always  specified  as  the  last  one  in the whole
parameter  line,  or  if  not explicitely specified, the name of the program
that  shall  be  executed  must  be  the  last  word  in the parameter line.
In-/Output redirection is possible.

Examples of valid usage:

 @{B}RunLame NV VirtualIntelligence                  @{UB};a demo

 @{B}RunLame NS C B CB EC VBR CL list >RAM:foo SYS:  @{UB};senseless, but works

 @{B}RunLame NOSCREEN CACHE B CL= C:dir RAM:         @{UB};senseless, but works

 @{B}RunLame SCREEN VISIBLE COMMANDLINE XCopyPro     @{UB};a copy program

 @{B}RunLame NS IC DC IB DB NCB COMMANDLINE=Resident @{UB};works
                                             ;(Resident is resident here :-)


NOTE:   when  you  use  filenames  containing  blank characters, you have to
enclose them into triple quotation marks:
 for AmigaShell from C=: @{B}RunLame """foo bar"""@{UB}
 for CShell (Unix port): @{B}RunLame \\"\\"\\"foo bar\\"\\"\\"@{UB}
Otherwise  the  shell  will strip away the quotation marks, and RunLame will
never  see  them,  thus  executing the command line without quotation marks,
which of course will interpret the blank characters as name delimiters.

@ENDNODE
##_____________________________________________________________________________

@NODE Configuring "Configuring RunLame"

                            @{U}Configuring RunLame@{UU}


@{U}Configuring for shell@{UU}:

At first the configuring procedure for shell users is going to be described.
As you know you have the possibility to use the built in @{"defaults" LINK Option_DEFAULTS} of RunLame
or  the  @{"current  system  settings" LINK Option_DEFAULTS} for some of the configuration parameters
(@{"VBR" LINK Option_VBR}, @{"CACHE" LINK Option_CACHE},...).  Those can  be overridden by  further specified  @{"options" LINK ShellOptions}
and  parameters.   Furthermore  you placed the documentation (@{B}RunLame.guide@{UB})
outside  the  AmigaGuide path (defined in @{B}ENV:AmigaGuide/Path@{UB}).  So when you
want  always  to  use  another configuration than the defaults, just make an
alias for the desired configuration.

Example:

 @{B}Alias RunLame 'RunLame NODEFAULTS SCREEN INVISBLE VBR LOOP API
                    GUIDENAME=Docs:RunLame.guide'@{UB}

 So  when you now type  @{B}RunLame@{UB},  it always opens the API, it loops and uses
 the  current  systems  setting except for the display which is degraded and
 black, and the VBR is always moved to $0.l. Additionaly the guide is found.


@{U}Configuring for Workbench@{UU}:

Workbench  users  just  can  do  the  same,  they  need  only to specify the
appropriate @{"tooltypes" LINK WorkbenchTooltypes} for the icon.

Now you can experiment a bit (follow the instructions below):

·@{B}MakeLink FROM RAM:DirLame TO RunLame@{UB}

·@{B}Copy RunLame.info@{UB} (which came with this distribution) @{B}TO RAM:DirLame.info@{UB}

·Edit the @{"tooltypes" LINK WorkbenchTooltypes} in this way:
 @{B}COMMANDLINE=dir
 APPICON=USE
 LOOP=YES
 DEFAULTS=NO@{UB}
 (the other @{"tooltypes" LINK WorkbenchTooltypes} keep the way they are)

·Now double click DirLame.

Now  an application icon named @{B}DirLame@{UB} should appear on the Workbench.  Drop
some  drawer  icons  into this and watch what's happening.  If you need such
gimmicks very often, you may draw a special icon for this purpose.

Using  RunLame  from  Workbench often shows up the problem, that the default
path  of the  @{"filerequester" LINK GUI_OpenFReq} (of the @{"GUI" LINK Option_GFXUSERINTERFACE}) is pointing to the directory where
RunLame  is  located.  This is annoying in the most cases.  So if you have a
special  directory  from  where you are used to start the @{"lame" LINK Lame_Explanation} programs, set
the @{"PATH" LINK Option_PATH} tooltype to this directory.


@{U}Configuring for Directory Opus@{UU}:

Directory  Opus  users may want to install RunLame as a button, which starts
all highlighted files in the file listview.

Enter  the  configuration  module  and the @{B}Buttons@{UB} section. Press one of the
still  unused  buttons.  Enter `@{B}RunLame@{UB}' for @{B}@{U}N@{UU}ame@{UB} string gadget.  Make a @{B}New
entry@{UB} which is @{B}AmigaDOS@{UB}.  Enter  `@{B}[path]RunLame [@{"options" LINK ShellOptions}] {f}@{UB}' in the @{B}entry@{UB}
string gadget (replace [path] by the path where RunLame is located).
Enter @{B}@{U}S@{UU}tack size@{UB} `@{B}4000@{UB}', @{B}@{U}P@{UU}riority@{UB} `@{B}0@{UB}', @{B}@{U}C@{UU}lose delay@{UB} `@{B}2@{UB}'.  Uncheck all entries
in  the  @{B}Flags...@{UB}  listview gadget.  Check @{B}Output window@{UB} and @{B}Do all files@{UB} in
the listview gadget. Click @{B}Okay@{UB}. Click @{B}Okay@{UB}. Click @{B}Save@{UB}. Click @{B}Okay@{UB}.

The  new  @{B}RunLame@{UB} button is now fully functional.  Highlight a @{"lame" LINK Lame_Explanation} file and
press the new button.  Voilā.

@ENDNODE
##_____________________________________________________________________________

@NODE ProblemsSolutions "RunLame `Problems - solutions - corner'"
@NEXT KnownBugs

                       @{U}Problems - solutions - corner@{UU}

 ·If you got this error message:
@{B}
                        Screenmode degrading failed!
                 Forbid all promotion utilities to promote:
                  "RunLame (Đ by Bilbo 1st of Hypenosis)"
@{UB}
  Then you have probably installed one of the screenmode promotion utilities
  (fi.   The Promotor, NewMode, ForceMonitor, PKludge).  This promotion tool
  will  then  promote  the compatibility screen too, what is a really stupid
  idea.  You should prevent the promotion utility from promoting all screens
  with the title "@{B}RunLame (Đ by Bilbo 1st of Hypenosis)@{UB}".

 ·After  having been degraded, the display snaps back to the normal previous
  mode  when  a  window  has been opened.  This window might be owned by the
  @{"lame" LINK Lame_Explanation}  program  or  any other  task.  The problem with this window is it's
  ability  to bring it's underlying screen to the very front of all screens.
  The  currently  frontmost  screen  now  forces  the  display  to  it's own
  screenmode,  thus  stopping  the  graphics  hardware displaying a degraded
  display.  This is multitasking, and this is Amiga - you cannot do anything
  against  this  without  violating  multitasking  rules.   Of  course it is
  possible to avoid this problem by hardware hitting, but this works against
  the  concept  of multitasking and will therefore not be done.  If you need
  this though, try @{"another degrading tool" LINK OtherDegraders}.

 ·The  sprite  DMA shows weird patterns, though you made RunLame degrade the
  display (which should turn off the sprites, too).  If this happens, one of
  the currently open windows became active.  All windows have an own pointer
  image,  which becomes active on window activation.  You may have installed
  an AutoPointer/SunMouse utility which activated a window after the sprites
  have  already  been  turned  off.  Avoid this by disabling the appropriate
  application (the window-activating one).  Another possibility is, that the
  launched  program  opened  a window which became active.  You can't easily
  work around the latter problem.

 ·The  program  you  want  to  start  is  self-detaching and the settings of
  RunLame  are  only  valid  until  the program has detached itself.  If the
  program  has  an  option  to  turn  off detaching, then use this option at
  starting the program to prevent detach.  Otherwise, bad luck.

 ·You have  @{"Enforcer" LINK Enforcer_Explanation} running and your system always hangs when you start an
  Program using the @{"VBRTOFAST|VBRTO0" LINK Option_VBR} option. See the Knows Bugs section for
  an  explanantion  for  this phenomenon.  Quit @{"Enforcer" LINK Enforcer_Explanation} before you use the
  @{"VBRTOFAST|VBRTO0" LINK Option_VBR} option.

 ·You press  `HELP'  in  the  @{"GUI" LINK Option_GFXUSERINTERFACE}, but no online @{"guide" LINK Option_GUIDE} opens.  Probably the
  documentation  (@{B}RunLame.guide@{UB})  is not  located  in  the  @{"AmigaGuide" LINK AmigaGuide_Explanation} path
  (defined  in  @{B}ENV:AmigaGuide/Path@{UB}).   You  may  add  the  location  of the
  documentation to the AmigaGuide path (which should increase search time of
  AmigaGuide  applications).   Another possibility is, to use the @{"GUIDENAME" LINK Option_GUIDENAME}
  option to specify the path/name of the documentation guide.

 ·When  you  use  filenames containing blank characters, you have to enclose
  them into triple quotation marks:
   for  AmigaShell  from  C=:  @{B}RunLame """foo bar"""@{UB}
   for  CShell (Unix port):  @{B}RunLame \\"\\"\\"foo bar\\"\\"\\"@{UB}
  Otherwise  the shell will strip away the quotation marks, and RunLame will
  never see them, thus sending the command line without  quotation marks  to
  System(),  which  of course  will think that the blank characters are name
  delimiters.   Let me point out that this is @{B}NOT@{UB} a bug of RunLame, learn to
  live with it.

 ·When  starting  RunLame from CShell, and you ask for the error cause using
  the  @{B}why@{UB} command, you will always get the message that no error occured,
  even if really an error occured.  This is @{B}NOT@{UB} a bug of RunLame, but of the
  CShell V5.31-.  If you rely on those error codes, use the AmigaShell of C=
  instead of the CShell.

 ·You  start  RunLame  with  the intention to display the CLI template using
  @{B}RunLame  ?@{UB}.  The template is displayed, but the shell does not allow any
  CLI  input.   Instead  of waiting for input, RunLame immediately opens the
  GUI.   It is probable that you are using CShell V5.20+ and RunLame resides
  in  the  script  path defined in the _path variable of the shell.  This is
  @{B}NOT@{UB} a bug of RunLame.  I reported this problem to the current developer of
  CShell, so this might be fixed in future.  In the meantime fix the problem
  by  placing  RunLame  somewhere  in  your DOS path which is defined by the
  AmigaDOS  command  @{B}path@{UB} (fi.: @{B}Path Work:BestToolEver ADD; Rename RunLame
  Work:BestToolEver/RunLame@{UB})  or specify the full path of RunLame's location
  in  the  filesystem  each time you want to use it (this might happen in an
  alias like this:  @{B}alias runlame Work:BestToolEver/RunLame@{UB}).

 ·You  tried  everything,  but  you  didn't  manage  to  run a @{"lame" LINK Lame_Explanation} program
  properly.  RunLame  is not able to fix very @{"lame" LINK Lame_Explanation} programming bugs, so you
  can assume, the programmer of the program is @{"lame" LINK Lame_Explanation} himself, or didn't have
  enough time to do a proper code. But nobody is perfect :-)
  Your  last chance  might be to try @{"other degraders" LINK OtherDegraders} available in the Amiga
  world.

@ENDNODE
